have long experience of inspecting sponsor-led academies, which tend to be scho</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ols which have replaced predecessors with challenging histories</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more recently there is growing ins</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">pection evidence about ‘converte</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r’ academies, which tend to be successful schools. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As outlined in the Annual Report 2012-13, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted will assess the impact </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of conversion to academy status on school performance in the coming year. This will include detailed reporting on how well new academies make use of their autonomy and freedom to innovate and raise standards. We will also report in more detail on the perfo</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rmance of free schools once more schools have been inspected in 2013/14.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Recent reports from Ofsted, such as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unseen Children: access and achievement in education – 20 Years On</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, and changes to inspection frameworks, have</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> collectively</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> put an increased focus</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on ensuring that the quality of education improves</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> especially in those schools that are in the most disadvantaged areas and where the gaps between the performance of disadvantaged students and their more advantaged peers differs most. In this submission,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the term ‘disadvantaged’ refers to those students from low income backgrounds that have been eligible for free school meals at any point in the previous 6 years (FSM6).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(a) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged chil</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">dren, and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(b) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Part (a)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Academies play a significant role in education, particularly</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in the secondary phase</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">On 3 September 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">there were 3,48</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> academies in England which accounted for 5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">% of all secondary school</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s and 9% o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> all primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Over half of secondary age students in England are now educated</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (55%)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The relative influence of the academy programme vari</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">es across certain regions. For example, 60% of secondary schools in the North East and North West remain in local authority control - double that of the East Midlands and the East of England. The East Midlands and London have the highest proportions of spo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nsor-led academies and the North East the lowest.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">extent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of the programme in the primary phase is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">limited. In</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> some areas fewer than 5% of primary schools have become academies; this includes areas such as Norfolk</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and East Riding, where overall </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">performance is weak.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Around </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">45</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">% of all academies are conve</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rte</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r academie</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Converter academies are more likely to be good or outstanding for their overall effectiveness than the average as these schools </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in the significant majority of cases are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">good or better when they convert. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As of 31 August</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, 88% of converter academies </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> good or better with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">over a third outstanding. Even so, there are variations in the overall effecti</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">veness of converter academies across</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> different regions. For example, 9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">4% of converter academies in the North West are good or better compared with 80% in Yorkshire and Humber.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is a concern that some converter academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, albeit a minority,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> struggle to maintain their previously high performance. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In the future</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> cha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nges to inspection arrangements, Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">will give</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more frequent attention to those schools at risk of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">coasting</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">declining in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">effectiveness. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Around </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">55%</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> all academies </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor-led. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">At 5</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">%, the proportion of good and outstanding </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor-led academies is lower than the figure for all schools nationally</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (78%)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The proportion of good or better sponsor-led academies varies widely across the country. Most sponsor-led academies in London are good or better (85%) compared with only a thi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rd of similar schools in the East of England (33%). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ponsor-led academies took on some of the most chronically underperforming schools in England with the intention of making a clean break with what had been a history of failure. There </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a sufficien</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t quantity of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have been established for long enough to begin to assess whether this ambition is being realised. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The sponsor-led academies that were established in the academic year 2007/08 are all secondary schools.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> In the first </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">year of est</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ablishment, the performance of these schools was 11 percentage points below the national level for the key GCSE benchmark of 5 or more GCSE passes at A* to C grade, including English and mathematics. This was exceptionally poor and reflected the weak educa</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">tional performance of the previous schools. Five years later, these schools had narrowed the gap by eight percentage points. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">important </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">contextual differences between converter academies and sponsor-led academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">For example, h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">alf of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor-led academies serve the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">most disadvantaged</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> communities compared to just over one in ten converter academies.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">By contrast, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">round a quarter of all converter academies serve the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">most prosperous</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> communities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> compared with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">only 1% of sponsor-led acad</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">emies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Sponsor-led academies that serve the most deprived communities are, on average, more successful in raising attainment for disadvantaged students than </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in sponsor-led academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in less deprived areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Overall, the proportion of students eligible for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> free schools meals</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (FSM6)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in sponsor-led academies is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">well </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">above the national average.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2013, h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">alf of all primary students (51%) and over two fifths of seco</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ndary students (44%) in sponsor-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">led academies were eligible for free school meals. This is above </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">local authority maintained averages (27% and 30%) and much higher than in converter academies (22% and 20%).</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Sponsor-led academies </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">also</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">educate</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> higher </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">than average </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">proportions of students from minority ethnic backgrounds. For example, two fifths of prima</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ry age students (40%) and just under a third of secondary age students</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (31%)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in sponsor-led academies are from minority ethnic backgrounds. This is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">higher, on average, than</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> local authority maintained </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (29% and 26%) and converter academies (26% and 2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">1%)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Sponsor-led secondary academies with high proportions of students from minority ethnic backgrounds are the most successful in terms of the end of Key Stage 4 attainment of disadvantaged students and reducing the size of the ‘attainment gap’. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Overall, students’ </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">benchmark </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">attain</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">at the end of Key Stage 4 is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">highe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in converter academies for all types of students</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> when compared with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">other types of school</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, 6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">% of students in converter academies achieved five good GCSEs including English and mathematics, 8 percentage points above the national average. In sponsor-led academies the average proportion was 51%. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2013, t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> average attainment of disadvantaged stu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">dents in converter academies was 46% compared with 40% in sponsor-led academies and 42% in local authority maintained schools. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Although the attainment of disadvantaged students is highest in converter academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> it is still well below that of students from</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more advantaged backgrounds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he ‘attainment gap’ at the end of Key Stage 4 between disadvantaged  students and their more advantaged peers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> wa</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s 27 percentage points </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in converter academies </span><span styl