n 2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> was lowest in the South East (32%) and South West (33%) compared with a group average of 40%. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In the North East</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Yorkshire and Humber and the East Midlands </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">attainment gap</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> between disadvantaged students and their more advantaged peers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> was</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> higher t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">han the group average by 6 percentage points</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Too few free schools have been open for long enough to analyse their impact</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on achievement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. Overall, London and the East of England have the highest proportion of free schools at 4%.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> This compares with only </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">1% in the North East.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The first 24 free schools opened in 2011. These schools were all inspected for the first time between 1 January and 30 July 2013: 18 were judged to be good or better for overall effectiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Part </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(b)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ll types of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">academ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">utilise their autonomy to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">innovate and raise </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">From January 2014, inspectors will pay particular attention to the ways in which these schools are using their additional freedoms to improve outcomes for all types of students. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Leaders have always </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">played a crucial role</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in driving improvements in education</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">their role </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is even more important in a system that gives greater freedoms and autonomy</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Above all else, we need to ensure that there are sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">numbers of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">high quality leaders to go around </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">as the system expands.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">These l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">eaders </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">must be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">well-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">equipped to use their additional </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">freedoms</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to raise standards for all groups of students. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> must be highly skilled in the areas of finance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> human resources</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> alongside demonstrating expertise in improvi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ng teaching.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> They </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">need to be able to deal with a challenging sponsor and to engage with business and commerce.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">vital</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that those organisations responsible for providing training </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">development </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> these leaders, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">such as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the National College, res</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">pond promptly and fully to their changing needs.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As the academy programme expand</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">care</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> must be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">taken when allowing schools to convert and when approving and registering free schools. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rusts </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">be able to demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> a strong track record of success before they are approved for expansion. Some</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> multi-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">academy trusts have been very successful and ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ve maintained </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">level of success whilst expanding. Others have found it harder to maintain quality when expanding quickly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">reach widens to beyond a more defined local area.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Free schools are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> registered initially as independent school</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ceive a pre-registration visit </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">from Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">prior to opening.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Almost all prospective free schools meet the requirements for registration</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. However,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> a gro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">wing number are set conditions </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">which must be met prior to opening.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Department for Education checks </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that the school has acted on Ofsted’s recommendations. Nevertheless, a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s the number of free schools grows, it is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">important</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that the qu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ality of successful applicants</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and the close monitoring of these schools, especially during their first two years, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> main</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">tained.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">welcomes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the Department for Education</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">recent</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> move to a regional structure.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> However, currently t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">here is a lack of synergy with the Ofsted regions.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> As this new system develops, it is important that there is clarity </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">about the relationship between the Department’s ‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Regional C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ommissioners’ and Ofsted’s Regional Directors so that there is a coherent high level focus on the quality of education </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">across</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> specific areas of the country.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authoritie</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most successful local authorities are those t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hat engage with all the schools in their areas, regardless of whether they are fully maintained, academies or free schools. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> typically view themselves as the ‘commissioner of education for the children and young people in their area’. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">f the local auth</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ority believe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that provision is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n’t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> good enough for the children then it challenges schools to do better</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, irrespective of status</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> have powers of intervention, the best are using them effectively (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e.g. by </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">issuing warning notices, s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ecuring interim executive boards and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">challenging </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">schools that are in categories of concern</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">); equally</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> where they do not have formal </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">powers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, they seek to influence the school or engage the D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">epartment </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ducation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to exercise its powers robustly. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Of the small number of free schools that have been inspected, the most successful </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> strong relationships with their local authority and actively build successful partnerships with other schools and agencies. In London, in p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">articular, there are typically</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strong links with the local authority and other schools in the community. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The best academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">work closely with other schools in their area (including maintained schools) to raise standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> work closely with the local authority to provide strategic capacity or additional school improvement capacity</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor other schools and/or academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">broker solutions, such as assisting with the appointment of effective interim leaders in problem schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">; and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">join and/or lead local partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Outside of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">multi-academy trusts, there are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">relatively </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">few ‘other organis</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ations operating between the Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and indivi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">dual schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’ that can demonstrate </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strong </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> helping schools to impro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ith </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">few exceptions, the dioceses are not proving to be catalysts for holding their schools to account</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aps</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in support</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">exist mainly for those </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">stand-alone </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">converter </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> struggle to maintain previously strong performance. In some instances, leaders </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">these schools feel or become isolated from successful practice elsewhere</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Although</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> some will </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">seek support from the local authority</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> there is often insufficient capacity to p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rovide </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the necessary level of support </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">or challenge. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Of the small number of free s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">chools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> inspected, the least successful</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> have limited partnerships or are only </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">beginning to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">develop them. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">weakest have few links with external partners and have faile</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d to act on the good advice they have been given.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ulti-academy trusts play a major ro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">le in the new school landscape. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The majority of sponsor-led academies are part of multi-academy trusts. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">here are now almost as many converter academies in these trusts</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> as there are in sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, with 560 academy converters compared with 680 spon</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sor-led academies. This reflects a significant change in the structure of the English education system. Some of these trusts now oversee more secondary schools than some local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most effective trusts have taken schools that were </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">underperforming and improved them comprehensively. On the basis of inspections to date, some are performing less strongly. However, because many trusts have recently taken on new academies, some of the largest trusts have had fewer than half of their schoo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ls inspected. As more academies in trusts are inspected, it will become clearer how the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> performance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> compares</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. From January 2014, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> will coordinate the inspection of the constituent schools in some weaker multi-academy trusts and report in detail on </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">our findings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Good governance is crucial to tackling underperformance and supporting improvement. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Academisation, especially where schools are part of a multi-academy trust, provides opportunities to enhance the quality of governance and to make </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strategic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">use of highly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">skilled </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">governors. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most successful trust governors often use their expertise of working with governing bodies in weaker schools to strengthen governance in others. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">successful trusts, the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> relationship </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">between board and local </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">level </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">gov</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ernance is clear;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the board take</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> responsibility for high level decisions on pay, appointments and policy and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the local governing body focus</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on implementation.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">When inspecting individual academies within a trust inspectors will pay particular attention o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n the quality of support that the academy receives from the shared MAT governance structures.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">here change is less well</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">managed, academisation can </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">blur</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> lines of accountability </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">between </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">local and trust level governance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">When converting, existing governors </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">do not always fully realise that their ‘powers’ will be weakened by conversion.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Where multi-academy trusts appoint an executive headteacher to oversee a number of schools, this can also lead to uncertainty in terms of wider accountability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply;  and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As of 3 September</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">onl</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">9% of primary schools were academies, educating around 7% of all primary pupils. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As such, primary academies have had</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">limited</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">on the wider education</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">landscape</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> than those in the secondary phase</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Around </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">90% of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">primary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">converter academies </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">were judged to be good or better for their overall effectiveness at their most recent inspection. Thus far, only seven sponsor-led a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">cademies have been inspected so</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> it is too early to report on their system-wide effectiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In 2013, pupils in primary ac</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ademy converters outperformed pupils in other types of schools at the end of Key Stage 2. For example, the proportion achieving a level 4 or above in reading was 90% in converter academies compared with 87% in local authority maintained schools and 75% in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor-led academies. A similar pattern exists for mathematics. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">schools?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">cluster</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> arrangements are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a potentially successful alternative </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">sponsor-led </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">status</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">se types of federations can be successful, especially where primary schools are small, and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">arrangements provide access to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">central resources, leaders and teachers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that would not otherwise be available</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. However, as with all groupings and ‘chains’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> decision</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to be made </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">about</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> who is responsible when one or more of the schools in the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">cluster</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> fails</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Securing i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nterim </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">xecutive </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oards as a means of providing failing schools with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> stronger leadership and governance is another </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">alternative strategy to full </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">academisation. In some instances</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, these highly skilled board members may</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> be involved in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oversight of several schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Unvalidated</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> examination results </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Except for 16-19 academies which are inspected under the Common Inspection Framework for Further Education Learning and Skills</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Figures are for primary and secondary academies where deprivation has been classified. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Deprivation is b</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ased on the Income Deprivation Affecting Children Index (IDACI) 2010. The deprivation of a provider is based on the mean of the deprivation indices associated with the home post codes of the pupils attending the school rather than the location of the schoo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">l itself. The schools are divided into five equal groups (quintiles) that are labelled from ‘most deprived’ to ‘least deprived’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">This includes f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ree </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">chools, University Technical Colleges and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">tudio </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">chools</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">All academ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ies, including free schools, have a l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">egal status as</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> independent schools and must meet the requirements of the Independent Schools Register. Those academies which acquire academy status under the Academies Act 2010 are deemed to have met those requirements upon opening and, therefore, do not u</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ndergo pre-registration inspections</span></p></body></html>